168. Pyymoeus. The qumaei were a nation of dwarfs, according to Pliny, in the extreme parts of India; according to Homer, Mela, and Strabo, in AEthiopia ; and according to others, in Scythia. They went mounted on goats and lambs, of proportionable stature, to make waragainst the cranes, which, at the approach of winter in Thrace, used to fly to the more genial climate of the Pygmaeans. The fable of their small stature is thought to have arisen from the etymology of the word, scil. πυγμὴ or πυγὰν, which means cubitus, a length of eighteen inches.
